{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211021/1948111901/0459.xml":{"full_text":"rr~nr~7\nT\nL\n\u00abi\n1 C\nh\nN\nTl\nr 11W r- rrl\n'\"MONTANA'S ONlV'*5t\u00c2TEWIOe INDEPENDENT NEWSPAPER\nH. S. BRUCE, Founder\nPublished weekly by The People's Voice Publishing Co. at 1205 Lockey Street\nHelena, Montana\nHARRY L. BILLINGS, Managing Editor\nP. O. Box 838\nPhone 26-J\nCO-OP PUBLISHING\nCO., HELENA, MONT.\n'Pot\nEntered as Second Class Matter December 7. 1939 at the Post Office at\nHelena, Montana, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nSubscription Price: $2.00 Year; Trial Subscription: Five Months $1.00\nNo Commercial Advertising except from Co-operative Business\ninstitutions accepted. Rates on application.\nNo Time For Slumber\nTuesday, November 2, 1948, can go down in history as\none of the great domestic victories achieved by the American\npeople.\nother past election days\u2014a day of misplaced trust,\nportance will be determined by the accomplishments of the\nnext few years.\nThe people voted strictly on the basis of issues. Having\nvoted, many are now inclined to rest on the laurels of victory.\nBut, there are other forces, who, though defeated at the elec\ntion, are not idle.\nIt is timely, therefore, following a couple of weeks of exul\n\u25a0the future may place it along side so many\nIt's im\nOr\ntation over the election results, for a spot of realistic appraisal\nof what is presently going on of some of the hurdles that must\nbe crossed during the 81st Congress.\nWhat about the campaign promises and the platform\npledges of the victorious Democratic party? Will they be\nfulfilled\nmajority?\nOne has only to read the daily press or listen to the radio\nprognosticators to realize the grave danger that the people may\nnot be able to cash in on their expressed desires of Novem\nber 2. A few examples may suffice to emphasize:\n9 The Democrats promised to halt inflation and set up\nstandby price control authority. Have you noticed the \"It can't\nbe done,\" or \"It's an economic impossibility\" refrains currently\nbeing chanted by the Kaltenborn Fulton Lewis Westbrook\nPegler axis?\nThe Democratic party promised repeal of the Taft\nHartley labor law. Again, you've probably noticed the mush\nroom-appearance of numerous labor relations \"experts\", who,\nvia every medium of publicity, are pleading the cause of this\nlaw; how it has \"stopped strikes\"; brought \"harmony\" to\nlabor-managem\u00e8nt relations, etc., ad nauseam. If you're in -1\ndined to doubt the law's viciousness, you've only to ask any\nworker who has been the victim of Taft-Hartleyism (union\nbusting, that is) or for that matter, *ask any fair-minded em\nployer who has found harmonious labor relations of long\nstanding disrupted by the red tape of the act.\nThe Democrats promised to really do something, about\nor will the fruits of victory be stolen from the\nthe housing crisis, slum clearance, the nation's health (or lack,\nthereof), to continue 90% of parity price supports as a floor\nunder American agriculture; to expand and broaden the social\nsecurity system to enact a 75c minimum wage law, etc., etc.\nWonderful! Wonderful!\u2014But\u2014after the election did you\nnotice the \"sage\" comment of 86-year-old Cong. Robert Dough\nton from down Dixie way: \"If the President's program is car\nried out taxes will have to be raised.\" He, as probable head\nof the powerful house committee on appropriations, may well\nbe able to see that there be no need for increased taxes\u2014par\nticularly excess profits taxes on corporations which have gone\nhog-wild in fleecing the public the last two years.\nLikewise, Democrats and Republicans promised effective\ncivil rights legislation for all Americans. But\u2014can they make\ngood on this promise, unless cloture is imposed in the senate? i\nAnd, if cloture is considered to cut off Dixiecrat filibustering,\ncan northern Democratic senators bring enough Republican\nSome Ominous Signs On the Economic Front\n\nThere's more to the recent stormy rumblings on\nthe New York stock market, in which $6 billions in\npaper losses occurred, than the oft-repeated asser\ntions that the slump was caused by the re-election\nof President Truman.\nIt may be too early for a definite\nassertion that the country's economy\nis on its way to another \"Black\nThursday\" which heralded the Octo\nber 1929 crash, but, it is a time for\nadded caution. During the past two\nweeks, nationally as well as in Mon\ntana, a number of signs have ap\npeared indicating that all is not well\nm.\n\u00bbWs\nisk L\nA\nwith our economy.\nExamine for a moment, if you will, what is hap\npening on the retail electrical, hardware and furni\nture markets*. Dealers in these durable goods lines\nin the state, in many instances, are worried over how\nslowly the public is buying their high-priced inven\ntories. Likewise, in Montana as in New York City\nnewspapers, advertisements emphasizing price\nslashes of a third to a half on furniture, are daily\noccurances.\nI\nlargest mills in the state,\nshutdowns, in Lincoln, Flathead, Lake and Sanders\ncounties, one very important economic fact stands\nout. Every operation that closes down, large or\nsmall, means a large number of men out of work.\nAlthough some of these men may be able to find\nemployment at Hungry Horse Dam, and in other\noccupations the next several months in that area,\nreports are there is a grave likelihood of widespread\nunemployment for at least the winter months. This\nnot only means deprivation for the unemployed and\ntheir families, it also spells tough sledding for many\nNote also that General Electric, L. C. Smith\nTypewriter, and a number of other big industries\nhave announced a cut in the work week from five\nj\nto four days This work week cut, they claim, is\nbecause production has caught up with demand.\nOf more immediate moment so far as Montana is\nconcerned, nas oeen the closing of many small lum-jtry\nber operations during the last couple of weeks in\nthe northwestern part of the state, capped by the\nindefinite shutdown of operations by the Somers\nLumber Co. The Somers mill is one of \u00bbthe two\nWhile the reasons are several for these various\nAROUND THE NEXT CURVE\n\n<0*\n\n\u00aba:\nf/A\n\n\u25a0$A N\n\n\n\n(A,\n\n/A\n4/.\ntrey/\nAWAKE UP/\n\n\nL\n'T\nv,\n\nvy\nfw.\ncc\n71\n\u25a0:-r\nI\nwm\n\u00e0\n7\nm\nm\n\n\u00a3s\u00bb5|\n\nm\n\nf\nJ'\nL\n\nrn\nKf o'\njo\nV 1\nc.\nA\n\nif.\nif\n7jr,\nr\n\nMm\nI\nk I\nf 1\n\nh\n'M\nr\nMm\nA\n7J:M\n\no\nm\nf\nr\nW 7,y\n(\u00a37 \"i\nGuerntey Montgomery tor Iht Economic Outtool. CIO.\n.u\nsenators around to assure the necessary two\nthirds vote?\nAdd to the post election \"It can't be\ndone\" barrage of press and radio, some of\nthe realities surrounding important congres\nsional committee chairmanships. Because of\ntheir poll tax-insured long-time tenure, a\nnumber of top committee spots will go to\nsouthern reactionaries.\nFor example, in addition to Congressman\nDoughton, Senator Maybank (S.C.), because\nof senate seniority rules, will likely head up\nthe senate banking and currency committee.\nThis is the committee which would initiate\nany price control legislation. His past rec\nord would not indicate any enthusiasm for\nsuch desperately needed legislation.\nTake also the powerful senate appropria\ntions committee. By seniority rules, dodder\ning old Senator. McKellar (Tenn.) will be its\nchairman. If his were to be the deciding\nvote on a program of low-cost housing, it's\na pretty safe bet there'd be no low-cost hous\ning, slum clearance projects, etc.\nThen again, a look at the likely chairman\nof the senate agricultural committee is not\nof such nature to bring comfort to small\ni\nwould be diametrically opposed to the big\nfellows and the speculators. Slated for that\nchairmanship is none other than Senator\nThomas (Okla.) whose chief claim to'infamy\nwas the discovery of his having flagrantly\nviolated all senate ethics by speculating in\ncotton and grain while a member of that im\nportant committee,\nthe situation. Unless the people very vigi\nlantly keep tabs on the congress, frequently\nremind the Democratic majority that they\nare expected to carry out their campaign\npromises in a reasonably satisfactory manner,\nthe danger is great that little will be legis\nlated for the lasting good of the entire nation.\nfarmers in instances where their interests\nThe above are a few of the realities of\nTELL US MORE. MR. WARDEN!\nThere's nothing like riding the tide. Do you re\ncall just a few short weeks ago when the daily news\npapers and the radio commentators were having a\nfield day destroying the good names of many fellow\nAmericans with ammunition supplied by the most un\nAmerican Thomas committee?\nRemember how the Great Falls Tribune, the com\npany sheets, and assorted drivel, carried screaming\npage one headlines on the sensational \"exposes\" by\none notoriety-craving female, Elizabeth Bentley, and\nher male opposite in the August-September \"spy\nhunt\", Whittaker Chambers? Of course you do.\nAnd, no doubt, if you'll think back a little earlier,\nyou'll recall the fiendish treatment handed such rep\nutable Americans as Dr. Edward Condon of the bu\nreau of standards, and Author Howard Fast, by these\nsame \"newspapers' 'and radio caluminators,\nBUT\u2014all that occurred BEFORE November 2 and\n8, .cspectively. The first date represents the elec\ntions, of course; the second, the day J. Parnall Thomas\nwas indicted for fraud by the department of justice.\nAND\n-with those two important dates having in\ntervened, lookie what we find now! I call your very\nparticular attention to O. S. Warden's Great Falls\nTribune, Wednesday, November 17, editorial page.\nThe high priest of all that's right and holy about\nthe Democratic party in Montana, has the following\nto say:\nTHE INVESTIGATOR ACCUSED\nJ. Parnell Thomas, who turned the spot-light of\npitiless publicity upon others without much discrim\nination, now finds that spot-light shining directly\nupon himself.\nIt may be conceded that an indictment is not\nBut it is also rightly expected and\ndemanded that a plaintiff or prosecuting witness,\nasking a judge to impose a penalty on others should\nIt is most de\nauthority\nvested in him by the law of the land and the faith\nof his fellow citizens for the double purpose of\nriching himself by debasting employes and defraud\ning the government. (Emphasis ours.)\nAs head of a congressional committee, Chairman\nThomas has interrogated many persons suspected of\nsympathizing with a foreign power. When these\npersons refused to answer his inquiries as to their\npeisonal and political affiliations he demanded their\npunishment for \"contempt of congress.\" Yet when\nhe was asked about certain suspected peculations,\n(Continued on Page Three)\na conviction.\nenter the court with clean hands.\nspicahle for an official t\no exercise an\nen\nsmall merchants who depend to a large degree\nsawmill and logging payrolls,\nj\non\nI 13 doubtful that this depressed lumber market\ncondition is localized to northwestern Montana and\ni northern Idaho. For some months now the retail\nlumber market has been tightening up The indus\nhas priced itself out of the market to a consul\nerable degree. It seems almost a safe prediction\nthat many thousands of timber workers throughout\nthe northwest will be without work before th^\nwinter is over.\nThese various signs of economic disturbances\nthe industrial front, and slipping farm prices, cou\npled with much pre-election advice by big business\neconomists to the late Mr. Dewey that he should\n(as President) engineer\nearly in 49 to break the inflation, to me, ominously\nindicate that the long-delayed post-war \"bust%\nsoon be upon us.\nlandish profit orgy by American business\nits twilight, and I'm very much afraid a lot of us are\ngoing to get hurt badly as the black night of d\u00e9pr\u00e9s\nsion descends upon us.\u2014 H. L. B.\non\n\"controlled\" recession\na\nmay\nThe \"Roman holiday\" of an out\nsee ms in","height":"20151","width":"13947"}}
